  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 19-22.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - Parallel passage: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 9:57-62",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "The would-be followers.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (On this section, cf. by all means Trench, 'Studies in the Gospels,' pp. 156-167: 1867.) Notice that St. Luke ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(1)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " places it almost at the beginning of the Great Episode, calling attention by it to the qualifications required of those who would follow the Lord Up to Jerusalem; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(2)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " adds a third example. So far as we have materials for deciding, the chronological position found in St. Matthew seems more probable. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 19.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And a certain scribe came;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Revised Version, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and there came a scribe.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Contrast the order in ver. 2. There the leper was recognized as such before ever he came  near, an emphasis being laid on him and his actions by the addition of \"Behold;\" here the official position is of but secondary importance. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "A certain",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Revised Version); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "εϊς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Hebrew numeral not uncommonly stands for an indefinite article (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 9:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". [Westcott and Hort]; 26:69). Trench's \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "one",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "scribe",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "...  with, perhaps, an emphasis on the 'one' to mark how unfrequent such offers were,\" is tempting, but improbable. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Scribe.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " St. Matthew alone records his profession. Perhaps because the distinction of Jewish classes presented itself more vividly to his mind than to St. Luke's. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And said unto him; Master;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " better, with the Revised Version margin, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "teacher",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "διδάσκαλε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It may be that he recognized one who was superior in an important branch of his own occupation, or, less probably, that he willingly accorded to him a title due to his occupation (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 3:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "infra",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 12:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "I will follow",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "thee",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἀκολουθήσω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "not",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐγὼ ἀκολουθήσω σοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Self is placed in the background; he is wholly taken up with that which he proposes doing. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Whithersoever thou goest",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Though, as a scribe, he would naturally prefer quiet. Contrast ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 6:66",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "περιεπάτουν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). But the discomforts would be greater than he expected. Observe, however, that there is no sign. in him of that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "φιλαργυρία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of which he has been accused (Cram. Cat.). Trench strangely favours the suggestion that he was Judas. Is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 14:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " a reminiscence of this offer? Matthew 8:19",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]